## Issues with this Infrastructure

### 1. Single Point of Failure (SPOF)
Every component lives on one server. If that server goes down (hardware failure, OS crash, power outage), the entire website becomes unavailable. There is no redundancy or failover.

### 2. Downtime During Maintenance
Deploying new code or updating the application often requires restarting Nginx or the application server. During that restart window, the website is inaccessible to users. There is no way to perform rolling deploys or zero-downtime updates with a single server.

### 3. Cannot Scale with High Traffic
A single server has fixed CPU, RAM, and bandwidth limits. If traffic spikes beyond those limits (e.g., a viral event), the server becomes overloaded and response times degrade or requests fail entirely. There is no horizontal scaling (adding more servers) or load balancing in this design.
